# Preventing Unnecessary Re-renders in React

There are several effective solutions depending on your component type:

## 1. **React.memo** (Function Components)

Wraps your component to skip re-renders if props haven't changed:

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(({ name, age }) => {
  console.log('Rendered');
  return <div>{name} - {age}</div>;
});
```

**With custom comparison:**
```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(
  ({ name, age }) => <div>{name} - {age}</div>,
  (prevProps, nextProps) => {
    return prevProps.name === nextProps.name; // Only compare name
  }
);
```

## 2. **useMemo** (Memoize Values)

Prevents child components from re-rendering due to new object/array references:

```jsx
function Parent() {
  const config = useMemo(() => ({ theme: 'dark' }), []);

  return <Child config={config} />;
}
```

## 3. **useCallback** (Memoize Functions)

Keeps function reference stable across renders:

```jsx
function Parent() {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Clicked');
  }, []); // Empty array = never changes

  return <Child onClick={handleClick} />;
}
```

## 4. **PureComponent** (Class Components)

Automatically does shallow prop/state comparison:

```jsx
class MyComponent extends React.PureComponent {
  render() {
    return <div>{this.props.name}</div>;
  }
}
```

## Complete Example

```jsx
const ChildComponent = React.memo(({ name, onAction }) => {
  console.log('Child rendered');
  return <button onClick={onAction}>{name}</button>;
});

function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Without useCallback, onAction changes every render
  const onAction = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Action!');
  }, []);

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Count: {count}
      </button>
      <ChildComponent name="Click me" onAction={onAction} />
    </>
  );
}
```

## ⚠️ Important Notes

- **React.memo** does **shallow comparison** by default—complex objects/arrays will always be "new"
- Use **useCallback/useMemo** with empty dependencies `[]` cautiously; if you need external values, include them
- Don't over-optimize early; measure with React DevTools Profiler first

