# Integrating Claude into Your Next.js App

The simplest approach is **Claude API directly with server-side streaming**. Here's why and how:

## Recommended Architecture

```
Next.js App (Client)
    ↓ (POST /api/chat)
Next.js API Route (Server)
    ↓ (streaming)
Claude API
    ↓ (stream back)
API Route streams to client
    ↓
Real-time UI updates
```

This gives you:
- ✅ Real-time streaming responses
- ✅ Server-side API key management (secure)
- ✅ Minimal setup
- ✅ Full control over context and memory

## Quick Implementation

### 1. **API Route** (`app/api/chat/route.ts`)

```typescript
import { Anthropic } from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";

const client = new Anthropic({
  apiKey: process.env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
});

export async function POST(request: Request) {
  const { messages } = await request.json();

  const stream = await client.messages.stream({
    model: "claude-opus-4.6",
    max_tokens: 1024,
    system:
      "You are a helpful assistant answering questions about user data.",
    messages,
  });

  // Convert to ReadableStream for Next.js
  return new Response(stream.toReadableStream(), {
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "text/event-stream",
      "Cache-Control": "no-cache",
      Connection: "keep-alive",
    },
  });
}
```

### 2. **Client Component** (`components/Chat.tsx`)

```typescript
"use client";

import { useState } from "react";

export default function Chat() {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState<any[]>([]);
  const [input, setInput] = useState("");
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  const handleSubmit = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (!input.trim()) return;

    const userMessage = { role: "user", content: input };
    setMessages((prev) => [...prev, userMessage]);
    setInput("");
    setLoading(true);

    try {
      const response = await fetch("/api/chat", {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify({
          messages: [...messages, userMessage],
        }),
      });

      if (!response.ok) throw new Error("API error");

      const reader = response.body?.getReader();
      const decoder = new TextDecoder();
      let assistantMessage = "";

      if (reader) {
        while (true) {
          const { done, value } = await reader.read();
          if (done) break;

          const chunk = decoder.decode(value);
          // Parse SSE format
          const lines = chunk.split("\n");
          for (const line of lines) {
            if (line.startsWith("data: ")) {
              try {
                const data = JSON.parse(line.slice(6));
                if (
                  data.type === "content_block_delta" &&
                  data.delta.type === "text_delta"
                ) {
                  assistantMessage += data.delta.text;
                  setMessages((prev) => {
                    const updated = [...prev];
                    const lastMsg = updated[updated.length - 1];
                    if (lastMsg?.role === "assistant") {
                      lastMsg.content = assistantMessage;
                    } else {
                      updated.push({
                        role: "assistant",
                        content: assistantMessage,
                      });
                    }
                    return updated;
                  });
                }
              } catch {
                // Skip non-JSON lines
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error("Chat error:", error);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-4 p-4">
      <div className="flex flex-col gap-2 h-96 overflow-y-auto border rounded p-4">
        {messages.map((msg, i) => (
          <div
            key={i}
            className={`p-2 rounded ${
              msg.role === "user" ? "bg-blue-100 ml-auto" : "bg-gray-100"
            } max-w-md`}
          >
            {msg.content}
          </div>
        ))}
        {loading && <div className="text-gray-500">AI is typing...</div>}
      </div>
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit} className="flex gap-2">
        <input
          value={input}
          onChange={(e) => setInput(e.target.value)}
          placeholder="Ask about your data..."
          className="flex-1 border rounded px-3 py-2"
          disabled={loading}
        />
        <button
          type="submit"
          disabled={loading}
          className="bg-blue-500 text-white px-4 py-2 rounded disabled:bg-gray-400"
        >
          Send
        </button>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 3. **Environment Setup**

```bash
# .env.local
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
```

## When to Consider Other Approaches

**Switch to the Agent SDK** if users need Claude to:
- Query databases or APIs to fetch their data automatically
- Execute multi-step workflows without user intervention
- Persist memory across sessions

**Add MCP servers** if Claude needs:
- Real-time access to external services (databases, SaaS APIs)
- Custom tools you control

**Use subagents** if:
- You need to process large datasets (split work across isolated agents)
- Different parts of the workflow need different system prompts

## Optimization Tips

1. **Add prompt caching** for repeated system prompts (saves 10% on cached input tokens):
   ```typescript
   system: [
     {
       type: "text" as const,
       text: "You are a helpful assistant...",
       cache_control: { type: "ephemeral" as const },
     },
   ]
   ```

2. **Upgrade to Sonnet 4.6** for better speed/cost balance with streaming

3. **Add conversation memory** — either store in your database or use the memory tool for cross-session persistence

4. **Consider batch API** if you're processing historical queries (50% cost reduction)

This setup is production-ready and scales to thousands of concurrent users. Start here, then add complexity only when you hit specific limitations.

Yes! This is a perfect use case for a **hook** — it's exactly what hooks are designed for. You can set up a hook that automatically runs your linting and type checks every time you edit a Python file, without needing to remember.

## Quick Setup

Here's how to create a hook that runs on every Python file save:

**Create `.claude/hooks/lint-on-save.ts`:**

```typescript
import { Hook, HookContext } from "@anthropic-ai/claude-sdk";

export const lintOnSave: Hook = {
  trigger: "PostToolUse",
  match: {
    toolName: "text_editor",
    action: "write",
    pathPattern: ".*\\.py$", // Matches .py files
  },
  handler: async (context: HookContext) => {
    const filePath = context.toolResult.path;
    console.log(`✓ Running linting checks on ${filePath}...`);

    // Run your linting tools
    const lintCmd = `python -m pylint "${filePath}" --disable=C0111`;
    const typeCmd = `python -m mypy "${filePath}"`;

    try {
      await context.exec(lintCmd);
      await context.exec(typeCmd);
      console.log(`✓ Passed all checks`);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(`✗ Linting failed:\n${error.message}`);
      // Optionally notify or fail the hook
    }
  },
};
```

This hook:
- **Triggers** automatically after you edit any `.py` file
- **Runs outside the LLM** — no token cost, instant feedback
- **Catches issues immediately** while you're still working on the file
- **Doesn't block your session** — it runs deterministically in the background

## What You Can Customize

- **`pathPattern`**: Match specific directories (e.g., `src/.*\.py$`) or exclude test files
- **Linting tools**: Swap `pylint`/`mypy` for `ruff`, `flake8`, `pyright`, or any combination
- **Error handling**: Make it fail the edit, notify you, or just log warnings
- **Conditions**: Only run on files in certain directories, or skip on specific branches

## Alternative: If You're Using Claude Code

If you're working in VS Code or JetBrains with Claude Code, you can use `/loop` for ongoing monitoring:

```
/loop 30s python -m pylint . && python -m mypy .
```

This checks your entire project every 30 seconds while you work. Good for catching issues across multiple files at once.

---

**Key advantage of hooks over `/loop`:** Hooks run only when you actually edit a file (not wasting cycles), and they're specific to the exact file you changed.

